A car travels at a constant speed of \(14.0 \, \text{m/s}\) around a level circular bend of radius \(45 \, \text{m}\). What is the minimum coefficient of static friction between the tyres and the road in order for the car to go round the bend without skidding? [University of Manchester 2008]

\section*{3.1}

\begin{align}
    x &= a \cos t \quad \text{(1)} \\
    y &= a \sin t \quad \text{(2)} \\
    z &= t \quad \text{(3)}
\end{align}

Squaring (1) and (2) and adding:

\[
x^2 + y^2 = a^2 (\cos^2 t + \sin^2 t) = a^2
\]

which is the equation of a circle. Since \(z = t\), the circular path drifts along the \(z\)-axis so that the path is a helix.

\section*{3.2}

\begin{align}
    a &= \frac{dv}{dt} = k^2 r t^2 \\
    v &= \int dv = k^2 r \int t^2 \, dt = k^2 r \frac{t^3}{3}
\end{align}

Power, \(P\):

\[
